Unless your file contains int(s), calling `sc.nextInt()` is not correct; and when it is correct, you would want to use `sc.hasNextInt()` (not `sc.hasNextLine()`). Here, you want to use `sc.nextLine()` to read each word (since there is one per line). Also, you should check that the file exists before attempting to read from it (so you can handle that condition reasonably). Finally, I would prefer [`try-with-Resources`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/exceptions/tryResourceClose.html) over explicitly managing the life-cycle of your `Scanner`. Like,

	File file = new File(args[0]);
	if (!file.exists()) {
		try {
			System.err.printf(&quot;Could not find &#39;%s&#39;.%n&quot;, file.getCanonicalPath());
			System.exit(1);
		} catch (IOException e) {
			e.printStackTrace();
		}
	}
	try (Scanner sc = new Scanner(file)) {
		while (sc.hasNextLine()) {
			String line = sc.nextLine();
			System.out.println(line);
		}
	} catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
		e.printStackTrace();
	}

